WEBVTT

00:06.131 --> 00:09.092
<i>[exciting music]</i>

00:09.092 --> 00:15.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.390 --> 00:17.267
<i>‐ My name is Jared Hobson.</i>
<i>I'm 41 years old.</i>

00:17.267 --> 00:18.727
<i>I'm from Wittmann, Arizona.</i>

00:18.727 --> 00:21.480
I've been a farrier
for about seven years now

00:21.480 --> 00:23.315
<i>and bladesmithing</i>
<i>for about two years.</i>

00:23.315 --> 00:25.275
<i>I've competed before</i>
<i>in other things‐‐</i>

00:25.275 --> 00:27.402
<i>like, I competed</i>
<i>in a blacksmith competition</i>

00:27.402 --> 00:30.239
<i>where we built horseshoes‐‐</i>
<i>but nothing like this,</i>

00:30.239 --> 00:33.825
so this is gonna be
pretty awesome, I think.

00:33.825 --> 00:36.286
<i>‐ My name is Joshua Frost.</i>
<i>I'm 43 years old.</i>

00:36.286 --> 00:38.288
I'm a steel nerd.
I can't help it.

00:38.288 --> 00:39.706
<i>I once made a post that said,</i>

00:39.706 --> 00:41.208
<i>"I love the smell</i>
<i>of martensite in the morning,"</i>

00:41.208 --> 00:42.834
<i>because I do.</i>

00:42.834 --> 00:45.796
<i>‐ My name is Jesse Delveaux.</i>
<i>I am 33 years old.</i>

00:45.796 --> 00:48.340
<i>I live in Cooperstown,</i>
<i>Wisconsin.</i>

00:48.340 --> 00:51.009
"Forged in Fire"
is my Olympics.

00:51.009 --> 00:52.844
<i>I'm absolutely ready.</i>
<i>I want to go and heat</i>

00:52.844 --> 00:55.138
some steel
and beat it into submission.

00:55.138 --> 00:59.309
<i>‐ I am Daniel Williams.</i>
<i>I'm from Maui, Hawaii.</i>

00:59.309 --> 01:03.605
People would describe me
as a gentle, loving giant.

01:03.605 --> 01:06.900
<i>And I have no clue what you</i>
<i>guys are gonna cook up for us,</i>

01:06.900 --> 01:09.528
but I assume it's gonna be
battling a robot

01:09.528 --> 01:12.823
or something completely
out of this world.

01:12.823 --> 01:15.409
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:15.409 --> 01:17.286
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:17.286 --> 01:19.037
of edged weapon‐making
competition

01:19.037 --> 01:20.998
specifically designed
to test every aspect

01:20.998 --> 01:22.958
of your edged weapon‐making
capabilities

01:22.958 --> 01:24.793
in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:24.793 --> 01:26.753
that will determine
which of you is our next

01:26.753 --> 01:28.297
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:28.297 --> 01:31.466
walking out of here
with a check for $10,000.

01:31.466 --> 01:33.844
All right, let's go ahead
and meet your judges now.

01:33.844 --> 01:37.514
Up first,
ABS Mastersmith J. Neilson.

01:37.514 --> 01:40.309
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

01:40.309 --> 01:41.560
David Baker.

01:41.560 --> 01:45.105
And last, edged weapon
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:45.105 --> 01:46.648
Gentlemen,
this is a competition

01:46.648 --> 01:48.483
I'm calling the cage match.

01:48.483 --> 01:52.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:52.112 --> 01:54.698
In the first round,
you are requested to forge weld

01:54.698 --> 01:57.284
together the steel
from the barbed wire

01:57.284 --> 01:59.328
inside of the cage
with the bars

01:59.328 --> 02:00.912
from the outside of the cage

02:00.912 --> 02:03.248
in order to make a signature
blade in your signature style

02:03.248 --> 02:05.042
that is between 8 and 10 inches
in length.

02:05.042 --> 02:06.418
<i>‐ Are you kidding me?</i>

02:06.418 --> 02:09.087
That barbed wire has just
got me going for a loop.

02:09.087 --> 02:10.255
I don't know how
I'm gonna use it.

02:10.255 --> 02:11.340
I don't know what I'm gonna
do with it.

02:11.340 --> 02:13.425
Um, kind of scary.
[laughs]

02:13.425 --> 02:15.135
<i>‐ Additionally, your</i>
<i>blade must include</i>

02:15.135 --> 02:17.346
<i>an integral handle</i>
<i>and knuckleduster</i>

02:17.346 --> 02:20.349
<i>with three points of contact</i>
<i>to the handle.</i>

02:20.349 --> 02:22.851
<i>‐ You evil, evil buggers.</i>

02:22.851 --> 02:25.771
It's definitely
a very difficult challenge.

02:25.771 --> 02:29.066
<i>Everything has to be</i>
<i>one solid piece.</i>

02:29.066 --> 02:31.276
‐ Now, in the second round,
you'll clean up your blades

02:31.276 --> 02:33.236
and add an edge
so that we can test them

02:33.236 --> 02:35.947
for strength and durability
in an ammo can stab

02:35.947 --> 02:40.202
and for edge retention,
in a denim bag slice.

02:40.202 --> 02:42.537
When the time runs out in the
first round of competition,

02:42.537 --> 02:45.123
one of you guys will have
to surrender your blade

02:45.123 --> 02:46.625
and leave The Forge.

02:46.625 --> 02:50.003
Good luck.
Your three hours starts now.

02:50.003 --> 02:52.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:52.464 --> 02:54.883
So we've got
four bladesmiths:

02:54.883 --> 02:56.927
Jesse, Joshua, Jared,
and Daniel.

02:56.927 --> 02:58.387
Can we get more Js?

02:58.387 --> 03:00.013
[laughs]

03:00.013 --> 03:01.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:01.014 --> 03:03.558
<i>‐ We need to get</i>
<i>the barbed wire</i>

03:03.558 --> 03:05.686
<i>out of the cage,</i>
<i>first and foremost.</i>

03:05.686 --> 03:08.146
The mistake that I made
is not cutting from the top,

03:08.146 --> 03:10.774
<i>so there was still a cage</i>
<i>in front of the barbed wire.</i>

03:10.774 --> 03:12.859
<i>So I wasted</i>
<i>a little bit of time</i>

03:12.859 --> 03:14.861
<i>getting that barbed wire</i>
<i>out of there.</i>

03:14.861 --> 03:16.405
‐ How does this go down, J?

03:16.405 --> 03:18.323
<i>‐ The trickiest part</i>
<i>of this challenge</i>

03:18.323 --> 03:20.701
<i>is making the integral handle.</i>

03:20.701 --> 03:21.952
<i>The handle has to be made</i>
<i>from the same metal</i>

03:21.952 --> 03:23.745
<i>as the rest of the blade.</i>

03:23.745 --> 03:25.330
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:25.330 --> 03:27.082
And one thing these guys
got to keep in mind‐‐

03:27.082 --> 03:30.377
<i>we're not only asking for</i>
<i>a blade but integral handle</i>

03:30.377 --> 03:32.421
<i>and a knuckleduster</i>
<i>that's gonna wrap around.</i>

03:32.421 --> 03:34.256
<i>They need about three times</i>
<i>the amount of steel</i>

03:34.256 --> 03:37.134
<i>they would normally forge.</i>

03:37.134 --> 03:38.385
<i>‐ I need to yank all these</i>
<i>bars off</i>

03:38.385 --> 03:39.928
<i>so I can get at</i>
<i>what's in the middle.</i>

03:39.928 --> 03:41.388
I decided to do
the canister

03:41.388 --> 03:44.099
because it's the easiest way
to get this done, I think.

03:44.099 --> 03:45.559
Barbed wire is mild steel,

03:45.559 --> 03:48.145
so you don't want that
anywhere near your blade edge,

03:48.145 --> 03:50.021
<i>so I kind of</i>
<i>strategically placed</i>

03:50.021 --> 03:52.232
<i>this little tiny piece</i>
<i>of barbed wire</i>

03:52.232 --> 03:53.984
<i>in a position</i>
<i>where I can remember it</i>

03:53.984 --> 03:56.236
<i>so it's not gonna come out</i>
<i>on the blade edge.</i>

03:56.236 --> 03:58.738
‐ Is that a good idea?
‐ Yeah.

03:58.738 --> 04:00.824
I mean, you could throw
as much barbed wire in there

04:00.824 --> 04:02.367
or as little.

04:02.367 --> 04:03.660
We didn't give them
a specification of how much.

04:03.660 --> 04:04.953
‐ All right.

04:04.953 --> 04:06.246
<i>‐ I'm at a loss.</i>

04:06.246 --> 04:08.457
<i>I don't know what to think</i>
<i>about this one.</i>

04:08.457 --> 04:10.000
This is something
that I've never done before.

04:10.000 --> 04:11.543
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:11.543 --> 04:12.961
<i>Right now, I'm working</i>
<i>on two billets.</i>

04:12.961 --> 04:16.423
<i>One is the barbed wire,</i>
<i>and one is the high‐carbon.</i>

04:16.423 --> 04:18.884
Then I'll go ahead and
forge weld those two together.

04:18.884 --> 04:21.303
‐ I really don't understand
what's going on

04:21.303 --> 04:23.597
with the two different
billets right now,

04:23.597 --> 04:26.308
unless he's planning on
forge welding those together.

04:26.308 --> 04:27.893
‐ I think‐‐well, he's got to.

04:27.893 --> 04:30.771
I mean, he's‐‐I wouldn't waste
time forging out two billets.

04:30.771 --> 04:33.023
<i>‐ The two billets</i>
<i>are coming out well,</i>

04:33.023 --> 04:36.735
but this is "Forged in Fire,"
so anything can happen.

04:36.735 --> 04:38.695
<i>‐ I think that the only thing</i>
<i>that I can do</i>

04:38.695 --> 04:40.530
is make a canister.

04:40.530 --> 04:42.032
This is my first time
doing a canister,

04:42.032 --> 04:43.450
so I'm kind of freaking out,
actually.

04:43.450 --> 04:44.910
[laughs]

04:44.910 --> 04:46.536
<i>I have to be careful</i>
<i>packing my can,</i>

04:46.536 --> 04:48.914
but I've never done one,
so I'm not exactly sure

04:48.914 --> 04:50.874
<i>where to put</i>
<i>the barbed wire in there,</i>

04:50.874 --> 04:52.918
<i>but I'm putting just two or</i>
<i>three pieces in my canister</i>

04:52.918 --> 04:55.879
<i>because I want my high‐carbon</i>
<i>steel and the 1095 powder</i>

04:55.879 --> 04:58.048
<i>to be most of my makeup</i>
<i>of my blade.</i>

04:58.048 --> 05:01.968
‐ I didn't actually see
Jared use any Wite‐Out.

05:01.968 --> 05:04.763
‐ By the time they draw
that canister out

05:04.763 --> 05:06.056
and then grind the edge,

05:06.056 --> 05:07.557
none of that mild steel
in the can

05:07.557 --> 05:09.434
is gonna be anywhere near
the edge anymore anyway,

05:09.434 --> 05:10.894
so that's a good way
of doing it.

05:10.894 --> 05:13.563
Why take the extra time?
‐ Yeah.

05:13.563 --> 05:14.981
<i>‐ The first thing I do</i>

05:14.981 --> 05:17.025
is cut off
my high‐carbon steel,

05:17.025 --> 05:20.445
<i>get a few pieces of the</i>
<i>barbed wire out of the middle,</i>

05:20.445 --> 05:22.906
and start building my canister.

05:22.906 --> 05:26.326
<i>I'm very concerned</i>
<i>about the high‐carbon steel</i>

05:26.326 --> 05:29.246
<i>being put into the canister,</i>
<i>because it's hard</i>

05:29.246 --> 05:33.625
to get enough heat to penetrate
the density of it.

05:33.625 --> 05:36.711
<i>I'm the last person to get</i>
<i>my canister in the forge,</i>

05:36.711 --> 05:38.588
and the clock
is ticking very fast.

05:38.588 --> 05:40.173
Come on, baby.

05:40.173 --> 05:43.635
Just a little more, please.

05:43.635 --> 05:44.886
‐ Daniel's going to the press.

05:44.886 --> 05:46.346
You can still see
the dark shadow.

05:46.346 --> 05:47.597
‐ Right.

05:47.597 --> 05:49.224
‐ It's dull red
'cause it's not hot enough.

05:49.224 --> 05:51.059
He's gonna be redoing that.

05:51.059 --> 05:54.396
‐ So I spend a good 15 minutes

05:54.396 --> 05:56.940
<i>extracting</i>
<i>the mild steel canister.</i>

05:56.940 --> 05:58.817
[bleep], it's all fractured.

05:58.817 --> 06:01.695
<i>Only some of my powder</i>
<i>is melted,</i>

06:01.695 --> 06:05.448
<i>and my sticks of carbon</i>
<i>are still solid within it,</i>

06:05.448 --> 06:08.952
<i>so I toss it away.</i>

06:08.952 --> 06:10.078
‐ What?
‐ Daniel's‐‐

06:10.078 --> 06:11.663
‐ Daniel's starting over, man!

06:11.663 --> 06:13.874
‐ I do like the fact
that he saw that,

06:13.874 --> 06:16.334
and instead of chasing
the problem, he's just done,

06:16.334 --> 06:19.379
drop it, and move on.

06:19.379 --> 06:21.506
<i>‐ My steel's in the forge,</i>
<i>and I'm just waiting</i>

06:21.506 --> 06:24.009
<i>to get it hot enough,</i>
<i>and I'm a little nervous.</i>

06:24.009 --> 06:27.470
If this part here isn't right,
I don't have a knife.

06:27.470 --> 06:29.806
‐ Looks good, man.
‐ The billet inside there.

06:29.806 --> 06:31.099
‐ Nice.
That's awesome.

06:31.099 --> 06:32.851
‐ But getting it off

06:32.851 --> 06:35.228
is gonna be another story.
Let's see if we can do it.

06:35.228 --> 06:38.565
‐ Joshua, he's trying to peel
the can off of his billet.

06:38.565 --> 06:41.026
I think he cut off
the very end of his can.

06:41.026 --> 06:42.110
‐ Good.
Good move.

06:42.110 --> 06:43.945
‐ When you chop
your two ends off,

06:43.945 --> 06:45.280
<i>the metal starts to kind of</i>

06:45.280 --> 06:47.782
<i>peel away</i>
<i>from the core billet.</i>

06:47.782 --> 06:49.200
Oh, yeah!

06:49.200 --> 06:50.577
<i>It's coming off like a dream.</i>

06:50.577 --> 06:53.121
Like a banana!

06:53.121 --> 06:55.707
<i>‐ I'm working on two billets.</i>
<i>It's a juggling act.</i>

06:55.707 --> 06:58.084
<i>Right now, my high‐carbon is</i>
<i>way ahead of my barbed wire.</i>

06:58.084 --> 07:00.420
I'm having some issues getting
the canister portion of it off.

07:00.420 --> 07:03.214
‐ So Jesse's billet looks
pretty compressed right now,

07:03.214 --> 07:05.425
but we do know that he used
the liquid paper

07:05.425 --> 07:07.344
on the inside of his can,

07:07.344 --> 07:09.137
so peeling this
is gonna be a challenge.

07:09.137 --> 07:12.182
‐ Yeah.
It should be interesting.

07:12.182 --> 07:13.350
<i>‐ Getting this canister off</i>

07:13.350 --> 07:15.685
is just an absolute pain
in my butt.

07:15.685 --> 07:18.688
[clanking]

07:18.688 --> 07:21.941
<i>It is on the floor</i>
<i>more than it's in the vise.</i>

07:21.941 --> 07:23.693
‐ Jesse's getting
extremely frustrated.

07:23.693 --> 07:25.278
‐ Just go in there,

07:25.278 --> 07:27.947
flatten the whole thing out,
and then grind.

07:27.947 --> 07:31.701
‐ Eventually, after many heats
and some perseverance,

07:31.701 --> 07:36.122
I get the canister mostly off.

07:36.122 --> 07:39.167
Right now, timeline, I gotta‐‐
I gotta pick up the pace.

07:39.167 --> 07:41.419
‐ Bladesmiths, you have just

07:41.419 --> 07:45.298
two hours remaining
to finish your work!

07:45.298 --> 07:47.175
<i>‐ It's stressful out here</i>
<i>on the Forge floor,</i>

07:47.175 --> 07:49.386
but it's no more stressful
than shoeing a horse

07:49.386 --> 07:51.096
that doesn't want
to have shoes put on it.

07:51.096 --> 07:52.722
[clanging]

07:52.722 --> 07:54.557
<i>I'm using what they call</i>
<i>a hot cut,</i>

07:54.557 --> 07:56.351
so I'm trying to cut
through the metal

07:56.351 --> 07:58.561
<i>to make my handle</i>
<i>for my knuckleduster.</i>

07:58.561 --> 08:00.855
‐ The only thing I don't like
about that idea

08:00.855 --> 08:03.441
is, you're gonna wind up
with a very skinny tang.

08:03.441 --> 08:05.318
It's not gonna be
comfortable to hold.

08:05.318 --> 08:07.654
But I'd forge out a billet
in the canister

08:07.654 --> 08:10.323
and draw everything out
into a long rattail,

08:10.323 --> 08:12.450
loop my rattail around,

08:12.450 --> 08:13.910
and then loop it back over
to make the knuckleduster.

08:13.910 --> 08:15.453
‐ Okay.

08:15.453 --> 08:16.663
‐ You could actually
just make a D‐guard,

08:16.663 --> 08:17.747
cut off an extra piece,
stick it in there,

08:17.747 --> 08:19.165
and MIG weld it in place.

08:19.165 --> 08:21.584
‐ That's not a bad idea.
‐ That'd be quick and easy.

08:21.584 --> 08:23.378
‐ Whatever they choose to do,

08:23.378 --> 08:25.296
make sure that
those fingers align

08:25.296 --> 08:26.715
to where you can make
a natural fist.

08:26.715 --> 08:28.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:28.383 --> 08:30.885
<i>‐ I'm struggling with getting</i>
<i>these three points of contact</i>

08:30.885 --> 08:34.013
so you can actually
use the knife.

08:34.013 --> 08:36.307
<i>I'm drifting three holes</i>
<i>into this thing.</i>

08:36.307 --> 08:38.017
This is gonna take
a whole lot of time,

08:38.017 --> 08:41.354
but aesthetically, I think
it's gonna be an advantage

08:41.354 --> 08:43.481
for me in the competition.

08:43.481 --> 08:45.275
Man, this is gonna suck.

08:45.275 --> 08:46.985
<i>If I don't get it right,</i>

08:46.985 --> 08:49.446
the steel on the end
of the holes could break off.

08:49.446 --> 08:51.990
<i>The finger holes</i>
<i>could be too small.</i>

08:51.990 --> 08:54.534
<i>There are a whole host</i>
<i>of things that could go wrong.</i>

08:54.534 --> 08:57.662
This is the ugliest thing
I've ever seen in my life.

08:57.662 --> 08:59.914
<i>But I think I'm getting</i>
<i>to a point</i>

08:59.914 --> 09:02.000
where if I make it
to round two,

09:02.000 --> 09:03.710
I'll be able to fix everything.

09:03.710 --> 09:06.838
‐ It's like a three‐fingered
knuckleduster over there.

09:06.838 --> 09:09.007
I don't know where your fourth
finger is supposed to go.

09:09.007 --> 09:12.594
‐ I think that's the pitfall
with most knuckleduster

09:12.594 --> 09:14.929
trench knives
is making the webbing

09:14.929 --> 09:16.473
in between the fingers
way too wide.

09:16.473 --> 09:18.141
‐ Yep.

09:18.141 --> 09:19.934
‐ Got to try to speed this up.

09:19.934 --> 09:24.522
Canister number two is same
chicken, different outfit.

09:24.522 --> 09:27.567
<i>I take it to</i>
<i>the hydraulic press two times</i>

09:27.567 --> 09:30.403
<i>to try to mate</i>
<i>my metals together inside.</i>

09:30.403 --> 09:32.614
‐ At this point, it wasn't hot
enough when he forge welded it.

09:32.614 --> 09:34.783
That's the problem.
‐ Yeah.

09:34.783 --> 09:37.327
I think I can do that.

09:37.327 --> 09:40.914
And I believe
that they have mated,

09:40.914 --> 09:44.417
so I try to cut
the can off of it.

09:44.417 --> 09:46.669
<i>I'm behind everybody.</i>

09:46.669 --> 09:48.338
[bleep] trash.

09:48.338 --> 09:50.465
There's a crack in my billet.

09:50.465 --> 09:53.510
[bleep], that's bad.

09:53.510 --> 09:55.095
<i>I need to start over.</i>

09:55.095 --> 09:56.179
[bleep].

09:56.179 --> 09:58.014
This could definitely
send me home.

09:58.014 --> 09:59.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:01.726 --> 10:04.604
<i>So my second canister, again,</i>

10:04.604 --> 10:07.565
failed to heat the high‐carbon
up to temperature.

10:07.565 --> 10:08.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:08.942 --> 10:11.111
‐ So Daniel's starting
his third canister.

10:11.111 --> 10:12.237
‐ Lord.

10:12.237 --> 10:16.741
<i>‐ In no way</i>
<i>am I gonna give up.</i>

10:16.741 --> 10:18.284
<i>‐ I've never made</i>
<i>a knuckleduster,</i>

10:18.284 --> 10:20.453
but I start out,
and I make the back curve

10:20.453 --> 10:22.247
of the knuckleduster

10:22.247 --> 10:25.125
and forge that center point
that would go

10:25.125 --> 10:28.086
<i>in between your middle finger</i>
<i>and your ring finger.</i>

10:28.086 --> 10:30.296
‐ Is Jesse making, like,
a musical symbol or something?

10:30.296 --> 10:31.881
‐ You're the master
bladesmith, man.

10:31.881 --> 10:33.925
You tell me what's going on.
I've never seen this before.

10:33.925 --> 10:35.343
‐ I can't tell you
what that is.

10:35.343 --> 10:39.806
‐ Right now, my process
pretty much sucks.

10:39.806 --> 10:41.307
<i>So we'll see</i>
<i>if I have enough time left.</i>

10:41.307 --> 10:43.184
<i>I'm working</i>
<i>my hardest right now.</i>

10:43.184 --> 10:46.020
<i>‐ I think I've gotten about</i>
<i>as far as I can go</i>

10:46.020 --> 10:47.147
with what I've got time for,

10:47.147 --> 10:49.107
so I'm gonna go ahead
and quench it.

10:49.107 --> 10:50.817
<i>Kind of a make‐or‐break</i>
<i>moment, you know?</i>

10:50.817 --> 10:54.028
Get it to critical temperature
and hope for the best.

10:54.028 --> 10:57.949
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:57.949 --> 10:59.993
I don't see any cracks
or anything in my metal,

10:59.993 --> 11:01.661
so I‐‐I think I'm okay
at this point,

11:01.661 --> 11:04.164
<i>and I just go</i>
<i>to hogging off metal.</i>

11:04.164 --> 11:09.502
‐ Bladesmiths, you have just 30
tiny little minutes remaining

11:09.502 --> 11:11.504
to finish your work.

11:11.504 --> 11:14.007
<i>‐ I messed up</i>
<i>my first two billets.</i>

11:14.007 --> 11:18.094
Now I'm trying to pull off
an emergency San Mai technique.

11:18.094 --> 11:23.308
<i>I grab this giant piece</i>
<i>of angle iron</i>

11:23.308 --> 11:26.019
because it's halfway
to a San Mai.

11:26.019 --> 11:29.522
<i>So I cut high‐carbon steel</i>
<i>off the cage again,</i>

11:29.522 --> 11:31.858
<i>and I throw pieces</i>
<i>of barbed wire</i>

11:31.858 --> 11:34.194
<i>into the spine of my knife.</i>

11:34.194 --> 11:36.571
Pretty concerned at this point
about getting it finished.

11:36.571 --> 11:39.741
<i>It is in the hands</i>
<i>of the knife gods.</i>

11:39.741 --> 11:41.159
‐ I'm not sure he's gonna
have enough steel

11:41.159 --> 11:42.660
to do all that integral work.

11:42.660 --> 11:44.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:44.579 --> 11:46.873
‐ Looks like, uh,
Joshua quenched.

11:46.873 --> 11:48.541
<i>‐ It's straight.</i>
<i>Beautiful.</i>

11:48.541 --> 11:51.085
<i>Fantastic.</i>
<i>I got a little bit of time.</i>

11:51.085 --> 11:54.255
<i>I'm just hogging off</i>
<i>as much material as I can.</i>

11:54.255 --> 11:56.883
Then I see
this little cold shut.

11:56.883 --> 11:58.384
<i>It's a weak point.</i>

11:58.384 --> 12:00.178
<i>Your knife</i>
<i>could very well break.</i>

12:00.178 --> 12:03.640
If that cold shut is deep,
your knife is trash.

12:03.640 --> 12:06.893
<i>You got to get it out</i>
<i>no matter what.</i>

12:06.893 --> 12:10.605
So I am leaning into this,
and I'm leaning it,

12:10.605 --> 12:13.066
<i>I'm leaning it,</i>
<i>I'm leaning it,</i>

12:13.066 --> 12:16.236
and it disappears.
[sighs]

12:16.236 --> 12:18.529
Thank you.
Fantastic.

12:18.529 --> 12:20.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:20.198 --> 12:23.701
<i>‐ The welding gods shine</i>
<i>upon me and decide</i>

12:23.701 --> 12:24.911
<i>that they're gonna let me</i>

12:24.911 --> 12:27.205
pull a shape out
of this knife,

12:27.205 --> 12:30.291
<i>and big blue helped me</i>
<i>to the motherland.</i>

12:30.291 --> 12:31.876
[laughs]

12:31.876 --> 12:33.586
‐ Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

12:33.586 --> 12:37.632
‐ Then I realize that I need
three points on my guard,

12:37.632 --> 12:40.593
<i>and I couldn't find</i>
<i>a drift anywhere,</i>

12:40.593 --> 12:44.264
<i>so I decide to make</i>
<i>an integral guard</i>

12:44.264 --> 12:45.890
<i>from a piece of rebar,</i>

12:45.890 --> 12:49.227
<i>which may or may not be</i>
<i>within parameters.</i>

12:49.227 --> 12:51.938
‐ What's Daniel welding?
The handle?

12:51.938 --> 12:53.064
‐ Interesting.

12:53.064 --> 12:56.234
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:56.234 --> 12:57.235
‐ Daniel's quenched.

12:57.235 --> 12:58.945
<i>‐ I'm pleasantly surprised</i>

12:58.945 --> 13:01.072
<i>by the fact</i>
<i>that I have a hardened edge,</i>

13:01.072 --> 13:04.617
and I may still be
in the running.

13:04.617 --> 13:06.661
<i>‐ With five or six</i>
<i>minutes left,</i>

13:06.661 --> 13:09.289
<i>I am feeling</i>
<i>absolutely rushed.</i>

13:09.289 --> 13:11.040
‐ Jesse, you just need
to quench, man.

13:11.040 --> 13:14.210
Stop playing.

13:14.210 --> 13:16.254
<i>‐ Once I see</i>
<i>that perfect temperature,</i>

13:16.254 --> 13:17.797
<i>it's into the quench I go.</i>

13:17.797 --> 13:19.090
Oh, come on!

13:19.090 --> 13:21.301
<i>Lost some hair on my arm,</i>

13:21.301 --> 13:24.929
but it ended up getting
nice and hard for me.

13:24.929 --> 13:26.472
I need to get over
to the grinder fast

13:26.472 --> 13:29.142
<i>and start hogging</i>
<i>off material.</i>

13:29.142 --> 13:34.480
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

13:34.480 --> 13:36.316
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

13:36.316 --> 13:40.111
This first round
of competition is over.

13:40.111 --> 13:41.696
‐ Whoo!

13:41.696 --> 13:43.656
<i>‐ So I'm not</i>
<i>particularly proud</i>

13:43.656 --> 13:45.158
<i>of the aesthetic of the blade,</i>

13:45.158 --> 13:46.784
but I am proud that I was able

13:46.784 --> 13:49.829
to get everything done
and make it work.

13:49.829 --> 13:52.498
‐ Bladesmiths, in this first
round of competition,

13:52.498 --> 13:55.501
we asked you guys to forge
blades between 8 and 10 inches

13:55.501 --> 13:58.546
with integral handles
and knuckledusters.

13:58.546 --> 14:00.173
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look

14:00.173 --> 14:01.507
at your work.

14:01.507 --> 14:03.009
Jared, you're up first.

14:03.009 --> 14:04.969
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:04.969 --> 14:07.305
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

14:07.305 --> 14:08.514
<i>‐ Well, everything</i>
<i>looks solid.</i>

14:08.514 --> 14:10.516
<i>I like the way</i>
<i>you put this together.</i>

14:10.516 --> 14:13.102
I'd love to see you
get this webbing right here

14:13.102 --> 14:14.353
to where it's comfortable.

14:14.353 --> 14:17.148
Right now, it's forcing
my fingers far apart,

14:17.148 --> 14:18.941
and it's digging really hard
into that knuckle.

14:18.941 --> 14:20.485
You got a lot of options,

14:20.485 --> 14:22.695
mainly because you've got
so much material in that blade,

14:22.695 --> 14:24.864
but I like
the idea of the shape.

14:24.864 --> 14:26.199
‐ All right, Joshua.
You're up.

14:26.199 --> 14:28.076
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:28.076 --> 14:29.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:29.702 --> 14:31.370
<i>‐ All right, Josh.</i>

14:31.370 --> 14:34.707
<i>Your handle here looks like</i>
<i>the most of a knuckleduster.</i>

14:34.707 --> 14:36.876
At this stage,
it is not functional.

14:36.876 --> 14:38.544
You don't have an anchor here,

14:38.544 --> 14:40.755
so even when you're chopping,
it's very loose.

14:40.755 --> 14:43.299
It's all the pressure goes onto
the index finger that's here,

14:43.299 --> 14:45.009
and there's just nothing
to hold on to here

14:45.009 --> 14:46.344
to get a good, firm grip.

14:46.344 --> 14:48.054
It's got a good look to it,

14:48.054 --> 14:50.765
but there's a lot of refining
to make it functional.

14:50.765 --> 14:53.559
‐ All right, Jesse, you're up.
Show the judges what you did.

14:53.559 --> 14:56.062
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:56.062 --> 14:57.480
<i>‐ All right, Jesse.</i>

14:57.480 --> 14:59.398
Right now, if you held it
this way, it's comfortable,

14:59.398 --> 15:01.234
but the index finger's
gonna be hitting right there

15:01.234 --> 15:03.152
when you're stabbing into it.

15:03.152 --> 15:06.239
I was watching the way
you were holding it‐‐this way.

15:06.239 --> 15:08.574
Not bad, because it takes
the index finger away

15:08.574 --> 15:10.243
from this area right here.

15:10.243 --> 15:11.911
It's still uncomfortable
in the webbing here,

15:11.911 --> 15:13.746
but this part is functional.

15:13.746 --> 15:14.914
The blade looks good.

15:14.914 --> 15:16.582
It's got a good,
aggressive look to it.

15:16.582 --> 15:19.085
Just some refinement so that
when you put your finger here,

15:19.085 --> 15:22.088
that webbing does not interfere
with your fingers.

15:22.088 --> 15:23.422
‐ Daniel, you're up.

15:23.422 --> 15:25.383
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:25.383 --> 15:27.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:27.760 --> 15:30.763
<i>‐ Daniel, definition</i>
<i>of "integral"?</i>

15:30.763 --> 15:33.766
‐ One piece of metal made
from the same extraction.

15:33.766 --> 15:37.937
‐ I commend you.
You had two flawed canisters.

15:37.937 --> 15:39.772
You never stopped,
you kept fighting,

15:39.772 --> 15:42.859
and you brought us
a finished piece,

15:42.859 --> 15:46.112
but this isn't one piece
from the same thing.

15:46.112 --> 15:49.157
This is rebar welded on.

15:49.157 --> 15:51.742
‐ Daniel, unfortunately,
because your blade

15:51.742 --> 15:54.036
doesn't have
an integral knuckleduster,

15:54.036 --> 15:55.746
it failed to meet
the parameters laid out

15:55.746 --> 15:57.373
for round one,
and for that reason,

15:57.373 --> 15:59.208
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

15:59.208 --> 16:00.960
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

16:00.960 --> 16:02.295
<i>‐ I'm a little disappointed,</i>

16:02.295 --> 16:03.629
<i>because I know</i>
<i>that in the long run,</i>

16:03.629 --> 16:04.964
<i>if given the chance,</i>

16:04.964 --> 16:07.550
<i>that I could probably</i>
<i>win this competition.</i>

16:07.550 --> 16:09.468
I knew when I finished
the blade that it wasn't up

16:09.468 --> 16:12.138
<i>to parameters,</i>
<i>but I turned in a blade,</i>

16:12.138 --> 16:14.015
<i>and I pulled it off</i>
<i>in 30 minutes,</i>

16:14.015 --> 16:15.349
so I'm proud
of myself for that.

16:15.349 --> 16:18.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:18.144 --> 16:19.645
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

16:19.645 --> 16:21.772
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

16:21.772 --> 16:23.232
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

16:23.232 --> 16:26.152
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

16:26.152 --> 16:28.988
by finishing the handles
and putting an edge on them.

16:28.988 --> 16:30.990
There will be
no additional materials

16:30.990 --> 16:32.366
provided to you in this round.

16:32.366 --> 16:35.494
However, you will be allowed
to weld additional metal

16:35.494 --> 16:37.288
to your blades
to address any issues

16:37.288 --> 16:39.415
with your knuckledusters
and handles.

16:39.415 --> 16:41.167
After this,
we're gonna be testing them

16:41.167 --> 16:45.630
for strength and durability
in an ammo can stab

16:45.630 --> 16:49.467
and for edge retention
in a denim bag slice.

16:49.467 --> 16:52.136
I remind you that after
your weapons have been tested,

16:52.136 --> 16:53.804
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

16:53.804 --> 16:55.556
and leave The Forge.

16:55.556 --> 16:58.392
Good luck.
Your two hours start now.

16:58.392 --> 17:01.354
<i>[rock music]</i>

17:01.354 --> 17:03.356
<i>‐ The first thing</i>
<i>that I'm going to do</i>

17:03.356 --> 17:06.359
is weld up that pinch point
in the front of the guard.

17:06.359 --> 17:09.570
<i>Just throw some weld in there,</i>
<i>try to get it built up</i>

17:09.570 --> 17:11.530
and comfortable
for whoever's using it.

17:11.530 --> 17:14.533
‐ Jesse‐‐looks like
he's kind of filled in

17:14.533 --> 17:15.701
that little crease...
‐ That's a good idea.

17:15.701 --> 17:16.953
‐ And rounded it out.

17:16.953 --> 17:19.163
‐ If he thins out
that center connection

17:19.163 --> 17:21.374
so it fits between
those two fingers,

17:21.374 --> 17:23.501
it might be
a really comfortable knife.

17:23.501 --> 17:25.544
<i>‐ Right now, it's just</i>
<i>a matter of shaping.</i>

17:25.544 --> 17:27.338
The difficult part is, is
instead of shaping wood

17:27.338 --> 17:30.716
or plastic or synthetics,
now you're shaping metal,

17:30.716 --> 17:33.511
<i>so it's gonna be a difficult</i>
<i>process to shape the handle</i>

17:33.511 --> 17:35.221
<i>and get it where I need to be.</i>

17:35.221 --> 17:37.848
‐ I think a mistake most smiths
make is, they make

17:37.848 --> 17:40.059
the knuckleduster
the same width as the knife,

17:40.059 --> 17:42.061
as opposed
to flattening it out

17:42.061 --> 17:45.648
so the webbing between those
fingers is a nice flat surface

17:45.648 --> 17:47.149
so when you drive forward,

17:47.149 --> 17:48.734
you're not trying
to cut your fingers off.

17:48.734 --> 17:50.236
‐ Right.

17:50.236 --> 17:51.571
<i>‐ The judges have</i>
<i>a valid concern</i>

17:51.571 --> 17:53.239
<i>about my knuckleduster,</i>

17:53.239 --> 17:55.741
so the first thing
I'm gonna do is address that.

17:55.741 --> 17:57.910
‐ Filing could take forever.
‐ Yeah.

17:57.910 --> 18:03.249
‐ What a tedious,
tedious process‐‐but precise.

18:03.249 --> 18:04.750
‐ It's easier to control.

18:04.750 --> 18:06.210
The rotary tools,
if you're not used to them,

18:06.210 --> 18:08.754
they can get away
from you quick.

18:08.754 --> 18:12.550
‐ Joshua had huge problems
with his finger rings.

18:12.550 --> 18:14.260
‐ Right now,
it is not functional.

18:14.260 --> 18:16.554
You can't get your fingers
in there comfortably.

18:16.554 --> 18:19.098
‐ He does have the advantage
in this round

18:19.098 --> 18:22.893
of being able to weld steel on.
‐ Oh, he's got the torch.

18:22.893 --> 18:26.272
‐ I have to cut out a piece
that contacted

18:26.272 --> 18:28.190
onto the handle
with the torch,

18:28.190 --> 18:29.942
<i>and I have to somehow</i>
<i>bend that out,</i>

18:29.942 --> 18:32.737
but I also have to add
another piece for it

18:32.737 --> 18:35.448
to be functional
as a knuckleduster.

18:35.448 --> 18:37.116
<i>If I don't get</i>
<i>this piece of metal</i>

18:37.116 --> 18:39.577
out of this little part here,
I'm done.

18:39.577 --> 18:42.288
I don't have anything
to compete with.

18:42.288 --> 18:46.959
‐ Bladesmiths, you have just
60 rapidly depleting minutes

18:46.959 --> 18:50.129
to finish your blades.

18:50.129 --> 18:52.965
<i>‐ Right now,</i>
<i>I'm just hogging off material,</i>

18:52.965 --> 18:54.634
getting everything
nice and straight.

18:54.634 --> 18:56.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:56.302 --> 18:57.595
‐ Knife's getting sexy.

18:57.595 --> 18:59.972
<i>‐ And that's when</i>
<i>I notice that there is</i>

18:59.972 --> 19:01.974
a slight delamination

19:01.974 --> 19:03.476
<i>in between the two billets.</i>

19:03.476 --> 19:05.645
Oh, what the hell am I doing?

19:05.645 --> 19:08.147
<i>I'm nervous about the forge</i>
<i>weld between the two billets,</i>

19:08.147 --> 19:10.274
but it's just keep on going
and keep on grinding

19:10.274 --> 19:12.276
<i>until I either grind</i>
<i>through it</i>

19:12.276 --> 19:14.320
<i>or until I have to come up</i>
<i>with another plan.</i>

19:14.320 --> 19:17.406
‐ If these welds don't hold
for Jesse right now,

19:17.406 --> 19:20.201
there's no time to restart.
‐ This sucks.

19:20.201 --> 19:24.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:24.872 --> 19:27.583
<i>‐ I think I've got my handle</i>
<i>pretty much wrapped up now,</i>

19:27.583 --> 19:29.001
and I'm ready
to kind of move on

19:29.001 --> 19:30.544
and see what I can
get done with my blade.

19:30.544 --> 19:35.216
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:35.216 --> 19:38.636
‐ Jared's blade seems like
it's very stout, J.

19:38.636 --> 19:39.887
‐ That's exactly
the word I'd use

19:39.887 --> 19:41.514
to describe it‐‐
a very stout blade.

19:41.514 --> 19:43.182
<i>‐ I'm not very good</i>
<i>on the grinder as far</i>

19:43.182 --> 19:46.477
as making a nice, good edge
and a good, strong tip.

19:46.477 --> 19:48.896
I am feeling anxious
because, being a farrier,

19:48.896 --> 19:51.357
you know, I can move metal,
I can make horseshoes,

19:51.357 --> 19:53.359
<i>but fit and finish</i>
<i>is definitely a weakness,</i>

19:53.359 --> 19:56.028
so I want to do everything
nice and smooth and easy

19:56.028 --> 19:57.905
so I don't‐‐I don't get
myself in trouble.

19:57.905 --> 20:04.954
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:05.788 --> 20:08.040
<i>‐ The plan is, weld this</i>
<i>to the front of the knife</i>

20:08.040 --> 20:11.335
<i>so I can have a guard</i>
<i>for my index finger,</i>

20:11.335 --> 20:14.547
<i>and I see that there's</i>
<i>a distance of about 1/4 inch</i>

20:14.547 --> 20:16.549
<i>between the thing</i>
<i>I just welded on</i>

20:16.549 --> 20:18.259
<i>and the actual blade,</i>

20:18.259 --> 20:22.471
and so I just want to
ease it in towards the knife,

20:22.471 --> 20:24.932
<i>and I'm easing it in...</i>

20:24.932 --> 20:26.892
[bleep].
The hell?

20:26.892 --> 20:29.478
<i>‐ And it breaks in half.</i>

20:31.522 --> 20:33.816
I need to get
this thing done,

20:33.816 --> 20:35.234
and I don't have
a whole lot of time.

20:35.234 --> 20:38.279
‐ 20 minutes, bladesmiths.

20:38.279 --> 20:40.865
<i>‐ Back to the grinder I go</i>
<i>with the rebar.</i>

20:40.865 --> 20:42.992
I have to make another one
of these things.

20:42.992 --> 20:45.202
<i>Heat it up with a torch,</i>
<i>bend it the same way.</i>

20:45.202 --> 20:48.622
<i>[rock music]</i>

20:48.622 --> 20:52.042
I may need it again.
[laughs]

20:52.042 --> 20:54.962
I weld it on there,
and it fits.

20:54.962 --> 20:56.547
<i>It's done.</i>

20:56.547 --> 20:58.883
And so I have
a functioning knife now.

20:58.883 --> 21:00.384
<i>So I start hauling ass.</i>

21:00.384 --> 21:03.304
Now it's starting
to look like a knife.

21:03.304 --> 21:04.722
<i>‐ Well, I finish grinding.</i>

21:04.722 --> 21:07.600
I get the best possible edge
I can get from grinding.

21:07.600 --> 21:10.436
And I've got 20 minutes left.
What do I do?

21:10.436 --> 21:12.646
<i>I'm running the risk</i>
<i>of doing more damage than good</i>

21:12.646 --> 21:14.482
<i>by trying to mess with it</i>

21:14.482 --> 21:16.650
<i>or try and refine it any more</i>
<i>than it already is,</i>

21:16.650 --> 21:19.320
so the best decision I can
think of is leave it alone.

21:19.320 --> 21:20.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:20.696 --> 21:22.323
‐ Jared has laid his knife
on the anvil.

21:22.323 --> 21:23.449
‐ No way.

21:23.449 --> 21:25.034
‐ Wow.
‐ 18 minutes left.

21:25.034 --> 21:26.535
‐ Oh, man.

21:26.535 --> 21:28.370
‐ Traditionally,
this has not gone well

21:28.370 --> 21:29.538
when a smith
has finished early.

21:29.538 --> 21:30.831
‐ Nope.

21:30.831 --> 21:32.291
<i>‐ I'm not gonna give in</i>
<i>to peer pressure.</i>

21:32.291 --> 21:33.793
I'm not gonna let them
sway me one way or another.

21:33.793 --> 21:35.169
My decision's my decision,
and I'm gonna stick to it.

21:35.169 --> 21:36.921
‐ [singsongy] Jared has made
the greatest blade

21:36.921 --> 21:39.548
ever made in this forge,

21:39.548 --> 21:43.052
because he's got 20 minutes
to sit around and stare at it.

21:43.052 --> 21:45.971
[laughter]
Awesome.

21:45.971 --> 21:49.058
