31:08.700 --> 31:12.204
<i>I'm doing an edge quench</i>
<i>because this blade</i>

31:12.204 --> 31:15.082
<i>has so much more surface area,</i>
<i>so much more steel.</i>

31:15.082 --> 31:19.419
<i>There's a larger potential</i>
<i>for something to go wrong.</i>

31:19.419 --> 31:22.881
That is a hard blade.

31:22.881 --> 31:24.049
Everything looks good.

31:24.049 --> 31:26.051
Happy about that.

31:26.051 --> 31:28.845
Now I can start hand‐‐
shaping my handle.

31:28.845 --> 31:30.097
<i>For the handle itself,</i>

31:30.097 --> 31:32.182
<i>I'm gonna be doing</i>
<i>an octagon shape.</i>

31:32.182 --> 31:35.769
<i>The octagon shape is gonna be</i>
<i>very well suited for gripping.</i>

31:35.769 --> 31:39.064
The next step
is to do a test fit.

31:39.064 --> 31:42.109
<i>Drilling through hardened</i>
<i>steel is definitely a bitch,</i>

31:42.109 --> 31:45.946
but actually seeing my axe
for the first time,

31:45.946 --> 31:47.823
<i>it definitely gives you</i>
<i>some extra energy,</i>

31:47.823 --> 31:50.242
<i>because you're in</i>
<i>that homestretch,</i>

31:50.242 --> 31:52.911
but the pressure is on
to get things done.

31:52.911 --> 31:54.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:54.496 --> 31:56.248
<i>‐ So it's the beginning</i>
<i>of the end,</i>

31:56.248 --> 31:58.750
<i>and I'm ready to get in there</i>
<i>and close it out.</i>

31:58.750 --> 32:01.086
Today I've got to drill
through the sockets

32:01.086 --> 32:04.798
and the hook and secure
the axe head to the haft,

32:04.798 --> 32:06.133
<i>and I'm trying to figure out</i>

32:06.133 --> 32:09.010
<i>how I'm gonna do this</i>
<i>on my drill press,</i>

32:09.010 --> 32:11.263
<i>but I just don't have</i>
<i>a secure way to do it.</i>

32:11.263 --> 32:14.057
<i>I'm gonna have to freehand</i>
<i>these holes.</i>

32:14.057 --> 32:15.684
<i>There's an inherent danger</i>

32:15.684 --> 32:17.602
<i>of drilling holes</i>
<i>like this by hand,</i>

